{"type":"message","id":"4e9c2a39","parentId":"6f05640d","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:19:10.986Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Interesting! The `2026-04-19/` directory was created, but it only contains `accounts/` and `accounts.json` - not the openclaw.json and other files we tried to copy. This means the rsync calls failed silently (they all have `|| true`).\n\nThis is very strange. The openclaw.json doesn't exist at the expected path, or permissions are wrong, or something else.\n\nWait - actually I think the issue is that `rsync_safe` is calling rsync with a source that doesn't end with `/` for files like `openclaw.json`. Let me check what the actual rsync command would be:\n\n`rsync_safe \"$OPENCLAW_DIR/openclaw.json\" \"$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/\"`\n\n\nWhen openclaw.json is a regular file, rsync with a trailing slash on the destination should copy it as a file into that directory, but it's coming up empty instead.\n\nLooking at the rsync_safe function definition, it properly passes both the source and destination with the `--delete` and `--exclude='.git'` flags, so the command construction itself appears correct. The issue must be happening at runtime.\n\nI'm wondering if the exit code handling is masking an actual failure. The `|| true` at the end of the rsync command should prevent the function from aborting if rsync fails, but maybe rsync is returning a success exit code even when it doesn't actually copy the file, or maybe the source path doesn't exist at the moment the function runs.\n\nLet me test the rsync command directly with verbose output to see what's actually happening."},{"type":"text","text":"еӨҮд»Ҫзӣ®еҪ•еҮ д№ҺжҳҜз©әзҡ„вҖ”вҖ”rsync йқҷй»ҳеӨұиҙҘдәҶгҖӮжЈҖжҹҘдёҖдёӢпјҡ\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_59822ehxpeo9_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"HOME=/home/halei; OPENCLAW_DIR=\"$HOME/.openclaw\"; BACKUP_REPO=\"/tmp/openclaw-backup-clone\"; DATE_DIR=\"2026-04-19\"; mkdir -p \"$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_