{"type":"message","id":"34240d6a","parentId":"e56e5c62","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:20:00.442Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"openclaw.json IS there! It was copied. The directory listing from earlier was misleading because it only showed \"accounts\" and \"accounts.json\" which are the OLD contents of that directory from before. After rsync ran, the new content was added.\n\nWait, but rsync should have deleted the old contents with `--delete` flag... unless the `--delete` was on the wrong path. Looking at the backup.sh:\n\n```bash\nrsync_safe \"$OPENCLAW_DIR/openclaw.json\" \"$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/\"\n```\n\nThis copies `openclaw.json` into `$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/` without a trailing slash on the source. \n\nWith a trailing slash on source, rsync copies the *contents* of the directory. Without it, rsync copies the directory itself. So `rsync -a --exclude='.git' \"$OPENCLAW_DIR/openclaw.json\" \"$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/\"` creates `$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/openclaw.json`, which is correct. The old \"accounts\" and \"accounts.json\" in the date dir are likely just remnants from before. The `--delete` flag only applies when the source is a directory with a trailing slash, so it's not affecting this particular copy.\n\nLet me verify whether the rsync commands for directories like agents/ actually ran, since the script might have exited with an error code that was being masked."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_3ccjs01jco46_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"ls /tmp/openclaw-backup-clone/2026-04-19/"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776572391172,"responseId":"06338ae7a71b8b706facb68f9f6e30e5"}}
