{"type":"message","id":"aa66d23d","parentId":"4e7e0899","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:20:14.062Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The rsync for openclaw.json worked. But other directories didn't get backed up. Looking at the backup.sh, the rsync_safe calls use paths like:\n```\nrsync_safe \"$OPENCLAW_DIR/agents/\" \"$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/\"\n```\n\nBut after the openclaw.json rsync, the destination for agents would be `/tmp/openclaw-backup-clone/2026-04-19/agents/` which should be correct. \n\nBut only openclaw.json and the old accounts directory are there. The rsync calls for agents/, cron/, etc. didn't seem to work. \n\nWait, I think I see the issue - the script uses `$HOME/.openclaw` but `$HOME` isn't set in the environment when running as a cron job or in certain contexts. \n\nLooking at the test output, the `openclaw.json` rsync succeeded with the full file list, but when I check the directory, only a few files appear - `accounts`, `accounts.json`, and `openclaw.json`. The agents, cron, and other directories that should have been synced are missing.\n\nI think the problem is that each rsync command is creating individual subdirectories at the destination. When I rsync `agents/` to `$BACKUP_REPO/$DATE_DIR/`, it's putting it at `/tmp/openclaw-backup-clone/2026-04-19/agents/` rather than placing the contents directly under `2026-04-19/`. So the files end up nested one level deeper than expected.\n\nLet me trace through the logic more carefully. The rsync output shows it transferred the openclaw.json file to the right location, but I need to verify what actually ended up in that directory to understand where the disconnect is.\n\nLooking at the directory listing, I see only accounts.json and openclaw.json are present. The agents directory that should have been synced from the source isn't there, which suggests the rsync_safe function might not be executing for all directories, or there's an issue with how the source paths are being resolved in the script.\n\nThe `|| true` at the end of each rsync_safe call is suppressing errors, so even if something fails silently, the script continues. This could be masking the real problem. I need to check whether the agents directory actually exists in the source OpenClaw path and whether rsync_safe is finding and transferring it correctly."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_2d6q5m0baz21_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"bash -x ~/.openclaw/workspace/skills/openclaw-backup/backup.sh 2>&1 | grep -E \"rsync|error|Error|skip|===|exit\" | head -40","yieldMs":115000,"timeout":120}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776572400512,"responseId":"06338af058924328ec2dd5a8fbc57780"}}
