{"type":"message","id":"a0682d5f","parentId":"cec55e26","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:37:00.332Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"So gosu IS at /usr/local/bin/gosu, and hermes binary exists and works fine when running as root. The issue must be something else.\n\nLet me think about what could cause \"hermes: command not found\". The entrypoint script does:\n1. `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` - this drops privileges and re-execs as hermes user\n2. Then it sources the venv and runs `exec hermes \"$@\"`\n\nWait, when the entrypoint is called with `hermes gateway run` (as the container is configured), and it's running as root, the script would:\n\n\n1. Detect root, check UID/GID env vars\n2. Change UID/GID if needed\n3. Run `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` - this switches to the hermes user\n4. Now running as hermes user, it sources the venv and runs `exec hermes gateway run`\n\nThe \"hermes: command not found\" error means that when gosu drops to the hermes user and execs the script, the hermes command isn't in PATH for that user. The entrypoint script doesn't export PATH, so when it's invoked via gosu, the hermes user's environment doesn't have the correct PATH to find the hermes binary."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_dqmqnn6o0im1_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest -c 'cat /etc/passwd | grep hermes'"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776573410221,"responseId":"06338ee2d07508dc295d562c17108311"}}
