{"type":"message","id":"12082814","parentId":"9e6e90ec","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:37:09.649Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me look at the entrypoint more carefully. It checks if running as root, then tries to change UID/GID if HERMES_UID/HERMES_GID env vars are set, then checks ownership of HERMES_HOME, then calls `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"`.\n\nBut when I ran without any env vars set, `id` showed `uid=0(root)`. That means the gosu part wasn't reached because it would have dropped to hermes user. Wait, no - when running `docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh ...`, the entrypoint is NOT run. The CMD is also overridden. So the entrypoint never runs when I use `--entrypoint /bin/sh`.\n \nSo when the actual container runs without overriding the entrypoint, it starts as root, checks the environment variables and home directory ownership, then uses gosu to switch to the hermes user before executing the main command. The error about `hermes: command not found` suggests the hermes binary isn't in the PATH when running as the hermes user, even though it should be accessible via the virtual environment."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_zhbvje1nmscj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest -c 'source /opt/hermes/.venv/bin/activate && hermes version 2>&1'"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776573420931,"responseId":"06338eed75331f6516a67b0019e09386"}}
