{"type":"message","id":"9897bda3","parentId":"963e36fd","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:37:26.546Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so when running directly as root, `hermes version` works fine. The issue must be something else. Let me look at the actual container again - it runs with `docker run ... nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest /bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'`. When bash runs as entrypoint with `-c 'hermes gateway run'`, the `hermes` command isn't found because it's in the venv but PATH isn't set up.\n\nLet me check the actual command that the container is running.\n\nWait, but the container is using `bash -c 'hermes gateway run'` as the CMD. This means it runs `hermes` without the full path. \n\nSo when the entrypoint executes with root privileges, it should activate the venv and run hermes, but something's going wrong with how the hermes command is being resolved when invoked through bash -c."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_m0iov65vkmfk_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run -d --name hermes-test-temp nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest /bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run' 2>&1; sleep 3; docker logs hermes-test-temp --tail 10 2>&1; docker rm -f hermes-test-temp 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776573438544,"responseId":"06338efe7ebe5aebaf59dd2958175f2b"}}
