{"type":"message","id":"11b8d294","parentId":"dbbb3127","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:37:40.675Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the `hermes gateway run` command works fine in the temp container. But the entrypoint `[/bin/bash]` with `[-c hermes gateway run]` doesn't work.\n\nWait - the command from `docker inspect` was:\n```\n[ \"-c\" \"hermes gateway run\" ]\n[ \"/bin/bash\" ]\n```\n\nThis is the wrong format. It should be `CMD [\"/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh\"]` or something. Let me look at how the container was actually started.\n\nWait, actually the image CMD `[\"/bin/bash\", \"-c\", \"hermes gateway run\"]` - when you override the entrypoint with `[\"/bin/bash\"]` and pass `-c hermes gateway run` as arguments... that should work. \n\nAh, I see the issue now. When Docker inspects a container, `Config.Cmd` shows the default command that runs when there's no entrypoint override, while `Config.Entrypoint` shows what's actually set. So for this container, the entrypoint is `/bin/bash` and the default arguments are `-c hermes gateway run`, which explains why the inspect output shows both.\n\nWhen I ran the temp container without overriding the entrypoint, it used that default `/bin/bash -c hermes gateway run`, but the error message about invalid command choice suggests the entrypoint is actually some shell script that tries to execute `hermes` as its own command, not as a bash argument.\n\nLet me just check the current running state of the actual container to see what's happening there."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_hjac0ejy2m3b_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker ps --no-trunc 2>&1"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776573450012,"responseId":"06338f0a4ee16bbf53cf50fa739ebddf"}}
