{"type":"message","id":"6a736282","parentId":"24135745","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:37:53.576Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The CMD is `/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'` - the entrypoint is `/bin/bash` and the CMD is `-c 'hermes gateway run'`. So when the container starts, it runs `/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'`. But the entrypoint is `/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh`. Wait, the Entrypoint is `/bin/bash` and the Cmd is `-c hermes gateway run`. \n\nActually, looking at the inspect output again: `Entrypoint: [\"/bin/bash\"]` and `Cmd: [\"-c\", \"hermes gateway run\"]`. The entrypoint takes precedence over the image's default entrypoint. \n\nSo the Docker runtime is executing `/bin/bash -c hermes gateway run`, but `hermes` isn't found in the PATH because it's installed in the virtual environment. The entrypoint script should be handling the PATH setup, but it's being overridden by the container's CMD.\n\nLooking at the inspect output again, the entrypoint shows as `[/bin/bash]` with CMD as `[-c, hermes gateway run]` вҖ” but the image's metadata indicated the entrypoint should be `[/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh]`. It seems the container was explicitly run with a custom entrypoint that bypasses the image's default startup script entirely.\n\nSince the running container has `/bin/bash` as its entrypoint, it executes `bash -c hermes gateway run` directly without ever sourcing the virtual environment. I need to fix the command path to point to the hermes binary in the venv."},{"type":"text","text":"еҺҹеӣ жүҫеҲ°дәҶгҖӮеҪ“еүҚиҝҗиЎҢе‘Ҫд»ӨжҳҜпјҡ\n\n```\n/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'\n```\n\n`hermes` е‘Ҫд»ӨеңЁ venv йҮҢпјҲ`/opt/hermes/.venv/bin/hermes`пјүпјҢдҪҶ PATH жІЎжңү venv и·Ҝеҫ„пјҢжүҖд»ҘжүҫдёҚеҲ°гҖӮе®№еҷЁеҗҜеҠЁж—¶ж №жң¬жІЎжңүжү§иЎҢ entrypoint.shгҖӮ\n\nжңүдёӨдёӘж–№жЎҲпјҡ\n\n**ж–№жЎҲ A**пјҡдҝ®еӨҚ Docker Compose/иҝҗиЎҢе‘Ҫд»ӨпјҢж”№жҲҗзӣҙжҺҘжү§иЎҢ hermes venv и·Ҝеҫ„\n\n**ж–№жЎҲ B**пјҡи®©е®ғжӯЈеёёиө° entrypoint.shпјҲйңҖиҰҒеҺ»