{"type":"message","id":"9e75a9c1","parentId":"7d8bc492","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:52:23.998Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The entrypoint just runs `exec hermes \"$@\"`. The image has no CMD, so docker uses the default. Since the entrypoint is `/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh` which does `exec hermes \"$@\"`, and the default CMD in the Dockerfile should be `hermes gateway run`.\n\nBut wait - the error happens in the `hermes gateway run` path specifically. The issue is that `hermes gateway run` tries to initialize the feishu_doc_tool which imports lark_oapi, and lark_oapi's ws/client.py causes a KeyboardInterrupt during import.\n\nActually wait - looking at the traceback again, it happened during `cli.show_banner()` which is in `cmd_chat`. \n\nSo it seems like `hermes gateway run` might actually be executing `cmd_chat` instead, which would explain why the banner is being built and the feishu_doc_tool is being imported when it shouldn't be in that code path."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fi25z08pehli_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest -c 'cat /opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh' 2>/dev/null"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776574336300,"responseId":"06339280b60ae542c7a9aeff419eb722"}}
{"type":"message","id":"12b32d9b","parentId":"9e75a9c1","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:52:24.751Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_fi25z08pehli_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"#!/bin/bash\n# Docker/Podman entrypoint: bootstrap config files into the mounted volume, then run hermes.\nset -e\n\nHERMES_HOME=\"${HERMES_HOME:-/opt/data}\"\nINSTALL_DIR=\"/opt/hermes\"\n\n# --- Privilege dropping via gosu ---\n# When started as root (the default for Docker, or fakeroot in rootless Podman),\n# optionally remap the hermes user/group to match host-side ownership, fix volume\n# permissions, then re-exec as hermes.\nif [ \"$(id -u)\" = \"0\" ]; then\n    if [ -n \"$HERMES_UID\" ] && [ \"$HERMES_UID\" != \"$(id -u hermes)\" ]; then\n        echo \"Changing hermes UID to $HERMES_UID\"\n        usermod -u \"$HERMES_UID\" hermes\n    fi\n\n    if [ -n \"$HERMES_GID\" ] && [ \"$HERMES_GID\" != \"$(id -g hermes)\" ]; then\n        echo \"Changing hermes GID to $HERMES_GID\"\n        # -o allows non-unique GID (e.g. macOS GID 20 \"staff\" may already exist\n        # as \"dialout\" in the Debian-based container image)\n        groupmod -o -g \"$HERMES_GID\" hermes 2>/dev/null || true\n    fi\n\n    actual_hermes_uid=$(id -u hermes)\n    if [ \"$(stat -c %u \"$HERMES_HOME\" 2>/dev/null)\" != \"$actual_hermes_uid\" ]; then\n        echo \"$HERMES_HOME is not owned by $actual_hermes_uid, fixing\"\n        # In rootless Podman the container's \"root\" is mapped to an unprivileged\n        # host UID вҖ” chown will fail.  That's fine: the volume is already owned\n        # by the mapped user on the host side.\n        chown -R hermes:hermes \"$HERMES_HOME\" 2>/dev/null || \\\n            echo \"Warning: chown failed (rootless container?) вҖ” continuing anyway\"\n    fi\n\n    echo \"Dropping root privileges\"\n    exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"\nfi\n\n# --- Running as hermes from here ---\nsource \"${INSTALL_DIR}/.venv/bin/activate\"\n\n# Create essential directory structure.  Cache and platform directories\n# (cache/images, cache/audio, platforms/whatsapp, etc.) are created on\n# demand by the application вҖ” don't pre-create them here so new installs\n# get the consolidated layout from get_hermes_dir().\n# The \"home/\" subdirectory is a per-profile HOME for subprocesses (git,\n# ssh, gh, npm вҖҰ).  Without it those tools write to /root which is\n# ephemeral and shared across profiles.  See issue #4426.\nmkdir -p \"$HERMES_HOME\"/{cron,sessions,logs,hooks,memories,skills,skins,plans,workspace,home}\n\n# .env\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/.env\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/.env.example\" \"$HERMES_HOME/.env\"\nfi\n\n# config.yaml\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/config.yaml\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/cli-config.yaml.example\" \"$HERMES_HOME/config.yaml\"\nfi\n\n# SOUL.md\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/SOUL.md\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/docker/SOUL.md\" \"$HERMES_HOME/SOUL.md\"\nfi\n\n# Sync bundled skills (manifest-based so user edits are preserved)\nif [ -d \"$INSTALL_DIR/skills\" ]; then\n    python3 \"$INSTALL_DIR/tools/skills_sync.py\"\nfi\n\nexec hermes \"$@\""}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":733,"aggregated":"#!/bin/bash\n# Docker/Podman entrypoint: bootstrap config files into the mounted volume, then run hermes.\nset -e\n\nHERMES_HOME=\"${HERMES_HOME:-/opt/data}\"\nINSTALL_DIR=\"/opt/hermes\"\n\n# --- Privilege dropping via gosu ---\n# When started as root (the default for Docker, or fakeroot in rootless Podman),\n# optionally remap the hermes user/group to match host-side ownership, fix volume\n# permissions, then re-exec as hermes.\nif [ \"$(id -u)\" = \"0\" ]; then\n    if [ -n \"$HERMES_UID\" ] && [ \"$HERMES_UID\" != \"$(id -u hermes)\" ]; then\n        echo \"Changing hermes UID to $HERMES_UID\"\n        usermod -u \"$HERMES_UID\" hermes\n    fi\n\n    if [ -n \"$HERMES_GID\" ] && [ \"$HERMES_GID\" != \"$(id -g hermes)\" ]; then\n        echo \"Changing hermes GID to $HERMES_GID\"\n        # -o allows non-unique GID (e.g. macOS GID 20 \"staff\" may already exist\n        # as \"dialout\" in the Debian-based container image)\n        groupmod -o -g \"$HERMES_GID\" hermes 2>/dev/null || true\n    fi\n\n    actual_hermes_uid=$(id -u hermes)\n    if [ \"$(stat -c %u \"$HERMES_HOME\" 2>/dev/null)\" != \"$actual_hermes_uid\" ]; then\n        echo \"$HERMES_HOME is not owned by $actual_hermes_uid, fixing\"\n        # In rootless Podman the container's \"root\" is mapped to an unprivileged\n        # host UID вҖ” chown will fail.  That's fine: the volume is already owned\n        # by the mapped user on the host side.\n        chown -R hermes:hermes \"$HERMES_HOME\" 2>/dev/null || \\\n            echo \"Warning: chown failed (rootless container?) вҖ” continuing anyway\"\n    fi\n\n    echo \"Dropping root privileges\"\n    exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"\nfi\n\n# --- Running as hermes from here ---\nsource \"${INSTALL_DIR}/.venv/bin/activate\"\n\n# Create essential directory structure.  Cache and platform directories\n# (cache/images, cache/audio, platforms/whatsapp, etc.) are created on\n# demand by the application вҖ” don't pre-create them here so new installs\n# get the consolidated layout from get_hermes_dir().\n# The \"home/\" subdirectory is a per-profile HOME for subprocesses (git,\n# ssh, gh, npm вҖҰ).  Without it those tools write to /root which is\n# ephemeral and shared across profiles.  See issue #4426.\nmkdir -p \"$HERMES_HOME\"/{cron,sessions,logs,hooks,memories,skills,skins,plans,workspace,home}\n\n# .env\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/.env\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/.env.example\" \"$HERMES_HOME/.env\"\nfi\n\n# config.yaml\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/config.yaml\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/cli-config.yaml.example\" \"$HERMES_HOME/config.yaml\"\nfi\n\n# SOUL.md\nif [ ! -f \"$HERMES_HOME/SOUL.md\" ]; then\n    cp \"$INSTALL_DIR/docker/SOUL.md\" \"$HERMES_HOME/SOUL.md\"\nfi\n\n# Sync bundled skills (manifest-based so user edits are preserved)\nif [ -d \"$INSTALL_DIR/skills\" ]; then\n    python3 \"$INSTALL_DIR/tools/skills_sync.py\"\nfi\n\nexec hermes \"$@\"","cwd":"/home/halei/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1776574344741}}
{"type":"message","id":"7a904aae","parentId":"12b32d9b","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:52:55.030Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The entrypoint uses `source` (bash) but the default shell is `/bin/sh`. When run as root, it uses `gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` which re-executes the entrypoint as the hermes user with bash as the shell. But `/bin/sh` on Debian is `dash`, which doesn't support `source`. \n\nWait, but the entrypoint is `/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'` passed as the command. So when docker runs the container, it:1. Runs `/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'` as root (override of entrypoint)\n2. Since it's root, it goes into the gosu block\n3. `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` replaces the current process with the entrypoint script, but `$0` and `$@` now contain the original command `/bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'`\n\n\n4. So it runs `gosu hermes /bin/bash -c 'hermes gateway run'`\n\nActually, let me re-read the entrypoint more carefully. The `gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` replaces the current process, so when gosu runs the entrypoint script again, `$0` is still `/bin/bash` and `$@` is `-c hermes gateway run`, which means bash gets invoked with the `-c` flag and the argument `hermes gateway run`.\n\nThe problem is that `source` is a bash built-in that dash doesn't have. When I tested this in a fresh container with the default command, it actually worked fineвҖ”it output \"Dropping root privileges\" and then \"Done: 0 new, 0 updated, 76 unchanged\" before failing on something else, so the entrypoint itself must be running with bash, not dash.\n\nThe `source` command appears in two places in the entrypoint, and both seem to work in the fresh container test. But with the mounted `/opt/data` volume from the host, the container is restarting (127), which suggests something about the data directory is causing the issue.\n\nLooking at the data ownership, the host directory is owned by `root:root`, but the entrypoint tries to change it to the hermes user. The `hermes-data` directory shows as `drwx------ 22 halei` on the host, which means the root user inside the container probably can't even access it to chown it. That's likely why the entrypoint fails immediately and the container exits with code 127.\n\nBut a code of 127 typically means \"command not found,\" not a permissions error. And I've tested with the mounted volume before without this issue. Maybe the entrypoint script itself isn't being found or executed correctly when the volume is mounted, or perhaps the hermes user doesn't have the right permissions even after the chown attempt fails silently.\n\nLet me reconsider: what if the entrypoint script runs successfully through the gosu step and activates the venv, but then `exec hermes \"$@\"` tries to execute the `hermes` command without the venv activated? I should try removing the custom command entirely and let it use the default entrypoint instead. Looking back at the logs from the fresh container run, I see the \"Dropping root privileges\" message followed by the sync completing, which suggests the entrypoint is executing, but then something's failing when trying to run the actual command. I'm realizing the issue might be with how the entrypoint script handles the `-c` argument passed to `/bin/bash`. When `gosu hermes` re-executes the entrypoint with those arguments, the `-c` flag and its parameter need to be properly parsed and passed through to the hermes command that gets exec'd at the end. I'm wondering if the issue is actually with how the `hermes` command itself is being invoked in gateway mode, rather than the shell initialization. Let me test this by running the container with an interactive shell instead to see what's actually happening."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_rnzwplic87ip_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker stop hermes-agent 2>&1; docker rm hermes-agent 2>&1; docker run -d \\\n  --name hermes-agent \\\n  -v /home/halei/hermes-data:/opt/data \\\n  -e HERMES_HOME=/opt/data \\\n  -p 18788:18788 \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  --log-opt max-size=10m --log-opt max-file=3 \\\n  nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest \\\n  2>&1 && sleep 5 && docker logs hermes-agent 2>&1 | tail -30"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776574344756,"responseId":"0633928951ed69f1d39dc5ba9eaf7761"}}
