{"type":"message","id":"6d3eae97","parentId":"93261555","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:56:25.385Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so the container starts, runs the entrypoint.sh which does `Dropping root privileges` and `Done: 0 new...`, and then... the shell exits. The entrypoint script seems to run its commands and then terminate.\n\nLet me re-examine the entrypoint script more carefully. After `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"`, the gosu process replaces the shell and runs the script again with the hermes user. Wait no - `exec gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` replaces the current process (the shell) with gosu, passing `$0` (which is the script path) and `$@` (the arguments) to gosu. So gosu runs `hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"`...\n \nActually, I think I'm misunderstanding the gosu syntax. The command should be `gosu hermes hermes \"$@\"` to run the hermes binary with the arguments, not `gosu hermes \"$0\" \"$@\"` which would try to execute the script path as a command. That's the bugвҖ”the entrypoint is trying to execute the script itself instead of the hermes command."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_xjcx4g8h1sgz_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest -c 'echo \"argv[0]=$0\"; echo \"argv[@]=$@\"' argv0_test 2>&1"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776574575756,"responseId":"06339370473bcd620c9fdf9bf0f4e009"}}
