{"type":"message","id":"b0449120","parentId":"a00e9c2c","timestamp":"2026-04-19T04:56:57.134Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The PID 1 process in the new container is `sh` (not `/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh`). This confirms that the entrypoint is being overridden - probably by Docker automatically adding `/bin/sh -c` prefix.\n\nBut wait - when I ran `docker run --rm --entrypoint /bin/sh ...`, I overrode the entrypoint. So this doesn't tell me what happens with the default entrypoint.\n\nLet me try a completely different approach. Let me run the container and immediately check what PID 1 is using the default entrypoint:\n\nActually, let me just check if the entrypoint.sh runs correctly by overriding just the command (keeping entrypoint):\n\n```\ndocker run -d --name hermes-test5 --entrypoint /opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh \\\n  -v /home/halei/hermes-data:/opt/data \\\n  -e HERMES_HOME=/opt/data \\\n  nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest \\\n  hermes gateway run\n```\n\nWait, but that's exactly what I did earlier with the explicit entrypoint and it still exited...\n \nOh, I see the issue now. The previous test actually ran without specifying an entrypoint, so Docker's default `/bin/sh -c` was used. That means the entrypoint.sh script itself isn't being executed at all - it's just being treated as a command argument to `/bin/sh -c`. That's why PID 1 is `sh` instead of the entrypoint script.\n\nBut there's a disconnect here. When I check `docker inspect` on the actual running container, it shows the entrypoint as `/opt/hermes/docker/entrypoint.sh`, yet PID 1 is still `sh`. Something's not adding up with how the container is actually being started.\n\nLet me think through this differently. The fact that \"Dropping root privileges\" appears in the logs tells me the entrypoint.sh is actually executing - that's printed by the script itself, not by hermes. So the script runs initially but then exits, which brings me back to why the container terminates right after.\n\nLooking at the entrypoint.sh flow: it does privilege dropping and skill syncing, then executes `exec hermes \"$@\"`. If no arguments are passed, hermes would invoke its default behavior. The issue is likely that hermes runs as a non-root user after gosu switches context, but then something in that execution path causes an immediate exit.\n\nSince I can't exec into a restarting container, let me trace through what actually happens by running it interactively instead - the `--rm` flag will clean it up automatically and let me see the actual output.\n\nActually, I think the real issue might be that `gateway run` in the background process exits after initialization. The logs show \"Goodbye!\" followed by a fresh \"Dropping root privileges\" cycle, which means PID 1 is restarting repeatedly. The container keeps restarting because the main process terminates, not because of a crash.\n\nLet me just update the docker-compose.yml to pass `hermes gateway run` explicitly and verify it actually works instead of continuing to debug this theoretically.\n\nActually, wait - the user mentioned the Feishu integration was working before and just stopped responding. That suggests either the Feishu bot token expired, the webhook verification is failing, or the gateway isn't even running. Since the container keeps restarting, the gateway process probably isn't staying up. I should check the Feishu configuration in the hermes-data directory to see if the bot credentials are still valid."},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_7dyuztea026u_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"docker run --rm -v /home/halei/hermes-data:/opt/data:ro --entrypoint /bin/sh nousresearch/hermes-agent:latest -c 'ls -la /opt/data/ 2>&1 | head -15'"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"minimax","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1776574595406,"responseId":"063393838adb60d2f43c0733d43bc88b"}}
